<!-- DEEP DIVE -->
<section class="oh-deep"><div class="ctr">
  <div class="badge badge-dark">FOUR DISCIPLINES OF FASHION FULFILLMENT</div>
  <h2 class="sec-h2">Why apparel deserves a different warehouse than electronics</h2>

  <div class="oh-deep-block">
    <h3>1. Size-level SKU tracking, not model-level aggregates</h3>
    <p>The biggest mistake fashion startups make is treating "Basic White Tee" as one SKU. It's not — it's 20 SKUs (5 sizes × 4 colors). Aggregating at model level guarantees overselling: when M runs out but the dashboard says "50 in stock," your customer orders M, you cancel, marketplace fines you, your rating drops. Recovering from a marketplace strike takes weeks.</p>
    <p>MTP's WMS tracks at SKU = model + color + size. Each physical unit has a unique barcode tied to a specific bin location. Channel sync runs at 800ms across Shopify, Etsy, Amazon EU, and any custom API. <strong>Result: 0 oversell incidents</strong> across our active fashion clients in the past 12 months. For a brand doing €50K/month, that's roughly €1,500-3,000/month in avoided fines and reputation damage.</p>
    <p>Setup is straightforward: send us your SKU master file, we generate barcodes and physical labels (€0.031/unit), receive your inbound shipment, scan each unit, place it in a designated bin, and inventory becomes visible in your channels in real time.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="oh-deep-block">
    <h3>2. Photo-documented returns protect margin and brand</h3>
    <p>Fashion returns run at 20-30% of orders — normal, because customers try clothes at home. About 3-5% of returns are fraudulent: customer wore it, washed it, decorated for a photoshoot, then "returned for refund." Without photo documentation, EU consumer protection law sides with the buyer. You eat the loss.</p>
    <p>Every return entering MTP's returns processing zone is photographed at 4 angles (clothing) or 6 angles (shoes) within 30 minutes of arrival. Operators check for: missing tags, wear traces (deodorant on collar, sweat stains, perfume), pet hair on dark fabrics, smoke odor, broken zippers, missing accessories. Photos are timestamped, geotagged, and stored in your WMS dashboard for 24 months.</p>
    <p>If a customer disputes the return, you have <strong>court-admissible evidence</strong> to deny the refund under EU consumer protection law (Directive 2011/83/EU Article 14 — significantly diminished value clause). Brands typically save 1-2% of revenue this way. For €50K/month, that's €500-1,000 in protected margin per month.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="oh-deep-block">
    <h3>3. War-resilient operations: the boring discipline of uptime</h3>
    <p>International brands ask the same question first: "Is Ukraine safe for fulfillment during the war?" The honest answer: war affects every aspect of logistics, but professional 3PLs have adapted. MTP has operated <strong>0 days of downtime since the full-scale invasion in February 2022</strong>. We've shipped 2.6 million parcels through every blackout, every air raid, every infrastructure attack on the energy grid.</p>
    <p>The infrastructure that makes this possible: 3 industrial generators (combined 350 kVA) sized to run the full warehouse for 72+ hours without grid power. Starlink for warehouse internet (independent from terrestrial fiber). Dual HVAC for climate control. Bunker-grade staff facility. 24/7 security with armed guards. Insurance via Lloyd's of London for inventory.</p>
    <p>Our Kyiv-region warehouses are 30+ km from the city center, in industrial zones with low strategic value. Statistically, the risk of physical damage to our facilities is lower than the risk of cyber-attack on a German 3PL — and we have insurance against both. International brands like our 14-day cancel notice (no long-term lock-in) — you can move out fast if anything changes. Most stay because the war hasn't disrupted shipping for two and a half years.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="oh-deep-block">
    <h3>4. EU shipping via Poland — the hidden advantage</h3>
    <p>Shipping from Ukraine directly to a German customer takes 8-12 days through Polish customs — too slow for fashion. Our solution: <strong>Polish forwarding hub</strong> in Rzeszów (200 km from our warehouse). Daily truck departures consolidate orders, cross the EU border at Korczowa, and dispatch through Polish postal/courier networks the same day. EU transit time: 3-5 business days, comparable to Amazon Prime EU.</p>
    <p>Cost: €2 per parcel for the consolidation step + €4-6 EU shipping (depending on weight and destination). Total: €6-8 per international order vs €10-15 if shipping directly from a German 3PL. The customer experience is identical — they receive a parcel from a Polish post tracking number, no customs forms to fill, no surprises at the door.</p>
    <p>For UK shipments, we add a UK consolidation step in London (post-Brexit customs handling). For DE/FR/IT/ES — direct from Poland. For PL — same-day local dispatch. For NL/BE — next-day from Polish hub. The whole network is invisible to your customer; they just see fast EU delivery.</p>
  </div>

</div></div></section>

